No, you shouldn't be expecting the `cache_key` to have `":cuda"` in it (and here, you're not controlling for where the substring is located; it should be at the end of the string), you should create a new key that is the user-provided `cache_key` plus the suffix `":cuda"` at the end. In other words, you _make_ the fully-qualified key; you don't expect to _get_ one.

Also, you can do this without any inline special cases on `ptr_lib_`. Suppose you have a function

```c++
const std::string
kernel::fully_qualified_cache_key(const std::string& cache_key, kernel::Lib ptr_lib) {
    switch (ptr_lib) {
    case kernel::Lib::cuda_kernels:
        return cache_key + std::string(":cuda");
    default:
        return cache_key;
    }
}
```

then you can first ask if the cache has a fully qualified key (which can be returned as-is), then ask if it has a plain `cache_key` (which needs to go through its `copy_to` and be added to the cache with a fully qualified key), then generate a new array as the second fallback. Newly generated arrays should go through their `copy_to` and only be stored in the cache with fully qualified keys.

The VirtualArray's `copy_to` (which is different from the generated array's own `copy_to`, just to be clear!) should not be calling the generator at all, even through `array()`. What `copy_to` means for a VirtualArray is to make it a VirtualArray-on-GPU (`copy_to` doesn't change array node type), which might still be ungenerated. It should copy the VirtualArray node but give it a new `ptr_lib` tag so that when arrays are asked for, they will end up on the appropriate device.

In summary,

   * VirtualArray has a new `ptr_lib_` tag to indicate what device its arrays will eventually end up on.
   * `VirtualArray::copy_to` just sets the value of that tag in a new copy of the VirtualArray node (lightweight to copy; it's just a bunch of references).
   * Every other `Content` subclass's `copy_to` actually copies (recursively) if the desired `kernel::Lib` is different from the actual one (for each node in the tree, recursively).
   * The `VirtualArray::array()` function needs to be `ptr_lib_` aware, so that it calls `copy_to` on any newly generated arrays to ensure that they're on the VirtualArray's own `ptr_lib_`, saves the final array in the cache with a fully qualified key, and checks the cache with two fallbacks instead of just one: fully qualified key (return what you've got because it's already in the right place), unqualified key (call its `copy_to` to ensure it's in the right place before saving it back to the cache with a fully qualified key), and generate anew.

